        <marginalia anchor_text="Marcellum" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Marcellus, prudens Dux more Romano: sed in bello gerendo magis strenuus, quàm prouidus: et ad terrendum hostes, 
                        sa[e]uè adhuc grassantes, audacior, quàm cautior. Potuisset esse virtus, quod euentus probauit vitium. Cauete animosi spiritus: 
                        et circumspectè ambulate: vt Heroes in nube.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Claudius Marcellus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Marcellus was a prudent leader in the Roman style, but in warfare more vigorous than prudent, and in frightening the enemy, 
                who were still raging fiercely, more bold than really careful. It could have been valor, which ultimately proved to be a flaw. 
                Watch out bold spirits and tread carefully, like heroes in the fog.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Marcellum etiam transfixum lancea prolabentem ex equo moribundum uidêre" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Egregij Marcelli mors. iactura nimis preciosa Reipub[licae] vsq[ue] adeò afflicta[e]. Sed Roma, sui similis, cum maximè victa, 
                        tum inuicta maximè. Etiam Fabio veteratore posteà defuncto, iuuenis Scipio pra[e]pollet omnibus; et sufficit solus domando Annibali. 
                        Iuuat interim patienter expectare infoelicium medioru[m] foelicem finem. Nec alia hîc opus consolatione. 
                        Tota ha[e]c Tragoedia, superstitibus Romanis in comoediam euadet.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Claudius Marcellus"/>
                    <person name="Fabius Maximus"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The death of the excellent Marcellus. An unduly precious loss for the Republic troubled to such an extent. 
                But being true to itself, Rome was most invincible when it was most defeated. Even later, after the death of the experienced Fabius, 
                the young Scipio is superior to all, and on his own is capable to subdue Hannibal. Meanwhile it is advantageous patiently to wait for a 
                successful end out of unfortunate intermediate stages. But there is no need here for another consolation. 
                This entire tragedy will turn out as a comedy for the surviving Romans.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Annibal" hand="Italian">
